    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1932-12-31T06:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1932-12-31T06:00:00-05:00" n="596"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d596">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">882.01 Foreign Control/446: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in Great Britain (<persName corresp="#p_AR1"
                            type="from">Atherton</persName>) to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">London</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1932-12-31T11:00:00+00:00"
                            >December 31, 1932—11 a.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received December 31—9 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>349. Department’s 302, December 29, 6 p.m. Following from <persName
                        corresp="#p_RSJ1">Reber</persName>:</p>
                <p>I saw Lord <persName corresp="#p_CVR1">Cecil</persName> last night and explained
                    to him the Department’s views regarding the new Liberian “law”, leaving with him
                    copies of it and of the letter presented by Mr. <persName corresp="#p_MCE1"
                        >Mitchell</persName>.</p>
                <p>While expressing strong disapproval of the recent Liberian action he felt that it
                    must be motivated by a feeling that Liberia could obtain money from sources
                    other than the Finance Corporation. He said that he had never given any
                    encouragement to this thought and he was at a loss to know where other funds
                    might be obtained. He was also sure that no such encouragement had been given in
                    Great Britain.</p>
                <p>He felt that he was not in a position to be of much assistance at the present
                    time but should the Committee be reconvened he would not lend support to a
                    unilateral infringement of the loan contract.</p>
                <p>Unless instructed to the contrary I propose to return to Geneva on Monday January
                    2nd and should the Department so desire I can make similar representations to
                    the League Secretariat.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_AR1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Atherton</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
